<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ba-trends-summary">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ba</group>
    <domain>business-analyst</domain>
    <summary>Routing index of six dominant BA industry trends for 2025-2026 with critical success factors, skill priorities, triggers, checklist, prompts, and verification.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>trends</tag>
      <tag>industry-analysis</tag>
      <tag>skill-evolution</tag>
      <tag>ba-2026</tag>
      <tag>routing-index</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
    <updated>2026-05-01</updated>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>BA Industry Trends 2025-2026</title>
    <summary>Read-only routing index of the six dominant BA industry trends for 2025-2026 (AI-enabled decision making, outcome-driven strategy, responsible innovation, operational resilience, digital trust, sustainability integration). Includes a critical-success-factor table, BA skill-evolution priority matrix, routing checklist, paste-ready briefing prompt, and verification steps. Contains no actionable workflow — each trend maps to a sibling methodology that owns the procedure.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Provides a single entry point for "what is trending in BA right now?" without forcing the agent to traverse six methodology folders. Each trend points to the actionable sibling that owns the procedure. Helps BA teams orient on the current landscape before drilling into specifics, and gives a stable reference for quarterly skill-planning conversations.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>User asks "which BA trends are relevant for 2025-2026?" or "what is hot in business analysis?"</item>
        <item>Deciding which BA methodology to study or apply next, based on industry direction.</item>
        <item>Orienting a new team or client on the current BA landscape before diving into specifics.</item>
        <item>Establishing quarterly learning priorities for BA team skill development.</item>
        <item>Building a slide, briefing note, or onboarding doc that needs a snapshot of BA market direction.</item>
        <item>Choosing which sibling methodology to load next — this index resolves the routing decision.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any actionable workflow (requirements elicitation, process analysis, stakeholder mapping) — load the linked sibling methodology directly.</item>
        <item>Generating prompts, checklists, or scripts for a concrete deliverable — those belong to the downstream methodologies.</item>
        <item>Empirical research or current-state assessment — this is a static snapshot, not live market data.</item>
        <item>Justifying a budget or business case — pair with primary sources (Gartner, Forrester, IIBA reports) before citing.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="top-six-ba-trends">
      <rule>
        <statement>Treat these six trends as routing signals: each maps to a dedicated sibling methodology that owns the actionable workflow.</statement>
        <rationale>This index is a snapshot; the sibling methodologies (ai-enabled-business-analysis, agile-ba-frameworks, process-mining-automation, data-driven-requirements, modern-ba-framework, ba-strategic-partnership) are where procedures live.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>AI-enabled decision making — integrating AI tools into requirements elicitation and analysis workflows. Route → ai-enabled-business-analysis.</item>
        <item>Outcome-driven strategy — shifting from feature delivery to measurable business outcomes as the unit of BA work. Route → modern-ba-framework.</item>
        <item>Responsible innovation — embedding ethics, governance, and bias-checking into AI project scoping. Route → ba-strategic-partnership.</item>
        <item>Operational resilience — designing processes and requirements for failure recovery, not just happy paths. Route → process-mining-automation.</item>
        <item>Digital trust — treating security, privacy, and auditability as primary requirements, not constraints. Route → data-driven-requirements.</item>
        <item>Sustainability integration — including environmental and social impact metrics in solution evaluation criteria. Route → agile-ba-frameworks.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="critical-success-factors">
      <rule>
        <statement>Quantify data quality before starting any AI-enabled BA initiative; 60% of AI projects fail due to poor data.</statement>
        <rationale>AI requirements analysis is only as good as the data it analyzes; the BA must assess data fitness before committing to an AI-augmented workflow.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Establish business process clarity before applying AI; 95% of enterprise AI projects fail without documented processes.</statement>
        <rationale>AI amplifies existing process structure — it cannot substitute for it. The BA must complete current-state modeling before AI tooling is introduced.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Stakeholder alignment — critical for adoption and value realization of any solution.</item>
        <item>Continuous learning — technology evolution requires ongoing skill investment.</item>
        <item>Ethical framework — trust and governance are strategic differentiators, not compliance checkboxes.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ba-skill-evolution-priorities">
      <rule>
        <statement>Prioritize AI/ML literacy and data analytics as immediate-action skills; treat process mining and automation analysis as 12-month targets.</statement>
        <rationale>The BA who cannot read a confusion matrix or query a data lake will be displaced by AI-assisted analysis; upskilling is not optional for 2025-2026 relevance.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>AI/ML Literacy — Critical priority, immediate action required.</item>
        <item>Data Analytics — High priority, immediate action required.</item>
        <item>Agile/Enterprise Agile Framework — High priority, ongoing.</item>
        <item>Strategic Thinking — High priority, continuous development.</item>
        <item>Process Mining — Medium priority, 12-month target.</item>
        <item>Automation Analysis — Medium priority, 12-month target.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <how-to>
      <step>Confirm the request maps to a routing question (trend snapshot, learning priority, briefing). If the user wants a deliverable, stop and load the actionable sibling instead.</step>
      <step>Pick the matching trend(s) from the top-six list. Note the sibling slug printed next to each item.</step>
      <step>Cite the relevant critical success factor(s) — data quality (60% rule) and process clarity (95% rule) are the two most cited anchors.</step>
      <step>If the conversation involves team upskilling, attach the skill-evolution priority list verbatim.</step>
      <step>Hand off: read the sibling methodology referenced in see-also and proceed there for any actionable work.</step>
      <step>Record the routing decision in the session log so subsequent turns do not re-resolve the same trend.</step>
    </how-to>
    <checklist>
      <check>Question is about BA trends, direction, or learning priorities — not a deliverable.</check>
      <check>Picked at least one of the six trends and named its sibling slug.</check>
      <check>Cited 60% data-quality and/or 95% process-clarity statistic when AI is in scope.</check>
      <check>Did not invent new trends, statistics, or sibling slugs beyond the six listed.</check>
      <check>For team-planning asks, included the skill-priority list with priority levels.</check>
      <check>Closed with explicit handoff to the sibling methodology if any procedural step is needed.</check>
      <check>Avoided giving time estimates ("2 weeks", "next quarter") — used qualitative priorities only.</check>
    </checklist>
    <commands>
      <command name="load-sibling-ai">Read skills/faion/knowledge/pro/ba/business-analyst/ai-enabled-business-analysis/methodology.xml</command>
      <command name="load-sibling-agile">Read skills/faion/knowledge/pro/ba/business-analyst/agile-ba-frameworks/methodology.xml</command>
      <command name="load-sibling-process">Read skills/faion/knowledge/pro/ba/business-analyst/process-mining-automation/methodology.xml</command>
      <command name="load-sibling-data">Read skills/faion/knowledge/pro/ba/business-analyst/data-driven-requirements/methodology.xml</command>
      <command name="load-sibling-modern">Read skills/faion/knowledge/pro/ba/business-analyst/modern-ba-framework/methodology.xml</command>
      <command name="load-sibling-strategic">Read skills/faion/knowledge/pro/ba/business-analyst/ba-strategic-partnership/methodology.xml</command>
      <command name="validate">python3 scripts/validate-methodology-xml.py skills/faion/knowledge/pro/ba/business-analyst/ba-trends-summary/methodology.xml</command>
    </commands>
    <prompt purpose="trend-briefing"><![CDATA[
You are a senior business analyst preparing a 1-page trend briefing for 2025-2026.

Source of truth: faion ba-trends-summary methodology (six trends + two critical success factors + six skill priorities). Do NOT invent additional trends or statistics.

Output template (markdown):

# BA Trends 2025-2026 — Briefing for {{audience}}

## Top Six Trends
1. AI-enabled decision making — <one-line implication for {{audience}}>
2. Outcome-driven strategy — <one-line implication>
3. Responsible innovation — <one-line implication>
4. Operational resilience — <one-line implication>
5. Digital trust — <one-line implication>
6. Sustainability integration — <one-line implication>

## Critical Success Factors
- Data quality — 60% of AI projects fail due to poor data; quantify fitness BEFORE the project.
- Process clarity — 95% of enterprise AI projects fail without documented processes; complete current-state modeling FIRST.

## Skill Priorities (for {{audience}}'s team)
- Immediate: AI/ML literacy, Data analytics
- Ongoing: Agile/Enterprise Agile, Strategic thinking
- 12-month: Process mining, Automation analysis

## Next Step
Route to: <sibling methodology slug from see-also that matches the audience's strongest pain point>.
]]></prompt>
    <verify>
      <step>Open this file and confirm exactly six items appear in the top-six-ba-trends list.</step>
      <step>Confirm both critical success factor statistics (60% data, 95% process) are present and unchanged.</step>
      <step>Confirm the skill-evolution priority list contains all six entries with priority labels.</step>
      <step>Confirm see-also lists exactly the six sibling slugs and that each slug exists as a folder under skills/faion/knowledge/pro/ba/business-analyst/.</step>
      <step>Run: python3 scripts/validate-methodology-xml.py skills/faion/knowledge/pro/ba/business-analyst/ba-trends-summary/methodology.xml — must report PASS with zero errors.</step>
      <step>Spot-check: when the agent answers a trend question, the response references at least one sibling slug from see-also and at least one of the two anchor statistics.</step>
    </verify>
    <warning>
      <p>This is a snapshot, not live market data. Do not cite as primary research. Pair with Gartner, Forrester, IIBA, or similar primary sources before using in a budget request, board paper, or external publication.</p>
    </warning>
